DyjsOnZT51qN7O1uSq7qhhVg1wyUXe1Y8HoCz6rblB10caCyc4akx_q_JyzOXMcrN1kJCSSfmZbG5DbHLAOHfJbn7QmuHJ8xBVDyUZLe3QY2Rthv-1NCvNPFP2Z620tFzokWKw6La8LM7bir8cFzk0WNbj3ke59xfrcWf8bY2LKfjiITwzCD_6u0QUU0meJFpizExya6xjwj8t5Wtfh3PfjcGGjw==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining class loading in code**\\n\\nI’m considering how to accept code, specifically with the AntClassLoader. The idea is to create a new instance that sets the path to the classes directory and adds a loader package root of \\\"org.apache.tools.ant.taskdefs.\\\" I’m exploring how forceLoadClass can bypass the parent class loader and how loadClass behaves with dependencies, especially regarding nested classes. If parentFirst is false, it may try the loader first for all classes before falling back to the parent. It's an interesting topic!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class resource access**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how class resources might be accessed. Using `Class.getResourceAsStream` could be tricky since the class file might not always be included. Maybe we could consider embedding class bytes in Base64, but that’s quite large for nested classes. Alternatively, I could check for ant jars on the filesystem. There's a possibility that the native image has a system property `java.class.path` to include the original classpath. I might need to create a resource config for class files.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Focusing on dynamic access calls**\\n\\nI’m considering the dynamic access call that might trigger while loading a duplicate class. The `AntClassLoader.defineClass` could potentially cover many call sites related to the `AntClassLoader`. This feels like an important focus area. I just need to edit the `ExecuteTest` to ensure that everything aligns with this idea. It seems like there’s a lot to do to improve the overall implementation and get it right!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_hcxeYMrGvwemzxtkeBBKZen2|fc_03491ca71478824a0169eff6ec0